# Exceptions

## Rules

- ❌ Do not use generic `\Exception`, `\RuntimeException`, or `\InvalidArgumentException` for **functional / domain failures** (insufficient stock, invalid order state, etc.).
- ✅ Each distinct business failure gets its **own exception class**.
- ✅ Name in **PascalCase** + `Exception` suffix: `InsufficientStockException`, `OrderAlreadyCancelledException`.
- ✅ One class per file; class name matches filename.

## Location

| Scope | Path | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Cross-module (thrown via `app/Contracts/`) | `app/Exceptions/{Domain}/` | `app/Exceptions/Catalog/InsufficientStockException.php` |
| Module-internal only | `Modules/{Module}/app/Exceptions/` | `Modules/Order/app/Exceptions/EmptyCartException.php` |

Cross-module exceptions live in `app/` so consuming modules can catch them **without** importing the implementing module.

## Implementation

- Extend `\RuntimeException` (or a project base exception if introduced later).
- Prefer **readonly constructor properties** for context (`productId`, `requestedQuantity`, etc.).
- Document `@throws` on public service and contract methods that propagate the failure.
- Tests assert the **specific exception class**, not `Exception::class`.

## Examples

```php
// app/Exceptions/Catalog/InsufficientStockException.php
class InsufficientStockException extends \RuntimeException
{
    public function __construct(
        public readonly int $productId,
        public readonly int $requestedQuantity,
    ) {
        parent::__construct("Insufficient stock for product [{$productId}].");
    }
}
```

```php
// Contract
/** @throws InsufficientStockException */
public function decrementStock(int $productId, int $quantity): void;
```

```php
// Test
})->throws(InsufficientStockException::class);
```

## Do not

- Do not reuse one exception class for unrelated failures.
- Do not place cross-module exceptions inside `Modules/*/app/Exceptions/`.
- Do not catch and swallow domain exceptions without a deliberate recovery path.
